Since you have renewed your policy yesterday and have been a customer for the last 6 years, you are entitled to renewal benefits as the policy "shall ordinarily be renewable except on grounds of fraud, misrepresentation," and renewal "shall not be denied on the ground that the Insured Person had made a claim or claims in the preceding policy years." You must have submitted the renewal request and premium before the end of the previous policy period or within a 30-day grace period after termination, though coverage is not available during the grace period.

Hydrocele is listed explicitly as a covered condition under the policy ("8. Hydrocele"), which implies it is eligible for claim, subject to policy terms, coverage limits, and exclusions.

To raise a claim for Hydrocele, you must submit the following original documents within the prescribed time limit after treatment:

i. Duly completed claim form;  
ii. Attending medical practitioner’s/surgeon’s certificate regarding diagnosis/nature of operation, including date of diagnosis and admission advice, supported by the prescription;  
iii. Medical history, bills (with charge breakdown) and payment receipts supported by prescriptions;  
iv. Discharge certificate/summary from the hospital;  
v. Cash-memo from Diagnostic Centre(s)/hospital(s)/chemist(s) with proper prescription;  
vi. Payment receipts from doctors, surgeons, anaesthetist;  
vii. Bills, receipt, and sticker of implants if any;  
viii. Any other documents required by company/TPA.

Claims must be submitted within specified time limits, for example, within 15 days from discharge for reimbursement of hospitalization and pre-hospitalization expenses, and 15 days from completion of post-hospitalization treatment for reimbursement of post-hospitalization expenses.

There are exclusions that may apply, but none specifically exclude Hydrocele. General permanent exclusions include conditions such as congenital external diseases, which Hydrocele is not categorized under. Expenses relating to treatment are covered if they are "Necessary, Reasonable and Customary Medical Expenses" under the policy terms.

Claim settlement will be processed within 30 days from receipt of the last necessary document, with interest payable on delayed settlement.

In conclusion, since Hydrocele is covered, your renewed policy after 6 years of continuous coverage allows you to raise a claim for Hydrocele. You must submit the required documents within the prescribed time limits to enable claim processing. There is no indication that your renewal status or prior duration as a customer impedes claim eligibility for Hydrocele.

The key ideals mentioned in the Preamble of the Constitution of India are:

1. To constitute India into a "SOVEREIGN SOCIALIST SECULAR DEMOCRATIC REPUBLIC."
2. To secure to all its citizens:  
   - JUSTICE, which includes social, economic, and political justice;  
   - LIBERTY of thought, expression, belief, faith, and worship;  
   - EQUALITY of status and of opportunity;  
3. To promote FRATERNITY assuring the dignity of the individual and the unity and integrity of the Nation.

These ideals together express the core values and objectives that the Constitution guarantees to the Indian people.

Parliament may alter the boundaries, area, or name of an existing State under Article 3 of the Constitution of India. Article 3 expressly provides that Parliament may by law—

(a) form a new State by separation of territory from any State or by uniting two or more States or parts of States or by uniting any territory to a part of any State;

(b) increase the area of any State;

(c) diminish the area of any State;

(d) alter the boundaries of any State;

(e) alter the name of any State.

Additionally, the proviso to Article 3 requires that no Bill for this purpose shall be introduced in either House of Parliament except on the recommendation of the President, and if the Bill affects the area, boundaries, or name of any State, the President must first refer the Bill to the Legislature of that State for expressing its views within a specified or extended period, and that period must expire before introduction.

Thus, Article 3 is the constitutional provision empowering Parliament to alter an existing State’s boundaries, area, or name, subject to the procedural requirement of prior recommendation by the President and consultation with the affected State Legislature.

"Hospital" means any institution established for in-patient care and day care treatment of disease or injuries and which either:

1. Is registered as a hospital with the local authorities under the Clinical Establishments (Registration and Regulation) Act, 2010 or under the enactments specified under Schedule of Section 56(1) of the said Act; OR

2. Complies with all the following minimum criteria:
   i. Has qualified nursing staff under its employment round the clock;
   ii. Has at least ten inpatient beds in towns with a population of less than ten lacs, and fifteen inpatient beds in all other places;
   iii. Has qualified medical practitioner(s) in charge round the clock;
   iv. Has a fully equipped operation theatre of its own where surgical procedures are carried out;
   v. Maintains daily records of patients and makes them accessible to the insurance company’s authorized representative.
